Sure! Once you have your SSL certificate, you’ll configure your Nginx server block to handle the reverse proxy and SSL termination. Here's an example configuration for `/etc/nginx/sites-available/mydomain.com`:

```nginx
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name mydomain.com www.mydomain.com;

    # Redirect all HTTP traffic to HTTPS
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}

server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name mydomain.com www.mydomain.com;

    # SSL certificate files (Certbot typically sets these up automatically)
    ssl_certificate /etc/letsencrypt/live/mydomain.com/fullchain.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/letsencrypt/live/mydomain.com/privkey.pem;
    include /etc/letsencrypt/options-ssl-nginx.conf;
    ssl_dhparam /etc/letsencrypt/ssl-dhparams.pem;

    # Reverse proxy to your web application
    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:5000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}
```

After saving this file, create a symbolic link in the `sites-enabled` directory and reload Nginx:

```bash
sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/mydomain.com /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t  # Test configuration for syntax errors
sudo systemctl reload nginx
```

This configuration:
- Redirects HTTP traffic to HTTPS.
- Terminates SSL at Nginx.
- Proxies traffic to your web app on `localhost:5000`.

