That's a great project idea! You can achieve real-time task updates using Firebase's Firestore database. Firestore's real-time listeners make it easy to reflect changes in your Vue.js app as they happen. Here's an outline of how you can set this up:

1. **Set up Firebase in your project:**
   - Go to the Firebase Console, create a new project, and set up Firestore.
   - Add your Firebase config to your Vue.js project by installing the Firebase SDK.

   ```bash
   npm install firebase
   ```

   - Initialize Firebase in your app:

   ```javascript
   // src/firebase.js
   import firebase from 'firebase/app';
   import 'firebase/firestore';

   // Your Firebase configuration
   const firebaseConfig = {
     apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
     authDomain: "YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN",
     projectId: "YOUR_PROJECT_ID"
   };

   // Initialize Firebase
   const firebaseApp = firebase.initializeApp(firebaseConfig);

   // Export Firestore database
   export const db = firebaseApp.firestore();
   ```

2. **Design the Firestore database structure:**
   - Create a `tasks` collection. Each task document can have fields like `title`, `description`, `assignedTo`, `status`, and `timestamp`.

3. **Implement real-time listeners:**
   - Use Firestore's `onSnapshot()` method to listen for changes to the `tasks` collection and update the UI in real time. Here's a simple example:

   ```javascript
   // src/components/TaskList.vue
   <template>
     <v-container>
       <v-list>
         <v-list-item v-for="task in tasks" :key="task.id">
           <v-list-item-content>
             <v-list-item-title>{{ task.title }}</v-list-item-title>
             <v-list-item-subtitle>{{ task.description }}</v-list-item-subtitle>
           </v-list-item-content>
         </v-list-item>
       </v-list>
     </v-container>
   </template>

   <script>
   import { db } from '@/firebase';

   export default {
     data() {
       return {
         tasks: []
       };
     },
     created() {
       this.fetchTasks();
     },
     methods: {
       fetchTasks() {
         db.collection('tasks')
           .orderBy('timestamp', 'desc')
           .onSnapshot(snapshot => {
             this.tasks = snapshot.docs.map(doc => ({ id: doc.id, ...doc.data() }));
           });
       }
     }
   };
   </script>
   ```

4. **Add functionality to create tasks:**
   - Create a form and use Firestore to add a new task to the `tasks` collection.

   ```javascript
   // src/components/AddTask.vue
   <template>
     <v-container>
       <v-form @submit.prevent="addTask">
         <v-text-field v-model="title" label="Task Title" required></v-text-field>
         <v-textarea v-model="description" label="Task Description" required></v-textarea>
         <v-btn type="submit" color="primary">Add Task</v-btn>
       </v-form>
     </v-container>
   </template>

   <script>
   import { db } from '@/firebase';

   export default {
     data() {
       return {
         title: '',
         description: ''
       };
     },
     methods: {
       async addTask() {
         if (this.title && this.description) {
           await db.collection('tasks').add({
             title: this.title,
             description: this.description,
             status: 'Pending',
             timestamp: firebase.firestore.FieldValue.serverTimestamp()
           });
           this.title = '';
           this.description = '';
         }
       }
     }
   };
   </script>
   ```

5. **Style using Vuetify:**
   - Use Vuetify components like `v-list`, `v-card`, and `v-btn` to create a polished design for your task tracker.

